<div id="p514" class="blockpost rowodd">
	<h2><span><span class="conr">#5&nbsp;</span><a href="viewtopic.php?pid=514#p514">2008-09-12 21:53:54</a></span></h2>
	<div class="box">
		<div class="inbox">
			<div class="postleft">
				<dl>
					<dt><strong><a href="profile.php?id=90022">sren</a></strong></dt>
					<dd class="usertitle"><strong>Member</strong></dd>
					<dd class="postavatar"></dd>
				</dl>
			</div>
			<div class="postright">
				<h3> Re: Top-BT: a BT client to speed downloading twice with less traffic</h3>
				<div class="postmsg">
					<p>Hi Dave,<br /><br />After quickly reading the posts on &quot;Latency Prioritizer&quot; through the link you provided, very interestingly, I found the ideas of doing pings to measure latency to peers are part of what we have implemented.<br /><br />In our Top-BT code, we not only do &quot;ping&quot; to peers, but also do &quot;traceroute&quot;. In this way, we can measure how many AS-hops (Autonomous System Hops) and link-hops to those peers. To balance download time and induced cross-ISP traffic, we also consider connections download rates and upload rates when deciding which peers to unchoke. <br /><br />We will be more than happy to share our experience with the community!</p>
				</div>
			</div>
			<div class="clearer"></div>
			<div class="postfootleft"><p>Offline</p></div>
			<div class="postfootright"><div>&nbsp;</div></div>
